Try changing the order of plotting the two classes (i.e. draw the saturated first then the non-saturated or the other way around). How does that impact the result?

Because there are so many more unsaturated data points, if you plot the saturated data points first and then plot the unsaturated data points on top of them, the saturated data is almost completely covered up (as shown by the graph on the left). Plotting the unsaturated data points first is a more accurate representation of the data because you can see both saturated and unsaturated data together on one graph (as shown on the right). However, this may still misrepresent how many saturated data points there are compared to unsaturated -- the graph on the right makes it seem as though the two groups are fairly similar in size, when in reality there is much more unsaturated data.

Can you find a better way to compare the two distributions?

The plot on the right can be improved upon by adjusting the alpha values and changing the marker sizes / shapes.

In[11]:

As shown above, placing the saturated data points on top of the unsaturated ones, but reducing the alpha value given to the saturated data points, allows us to present a more balanced representation of what the data looks like. From this visual, it is clear that there are much more unsaturated data points; however, we still see the areas where high saturation data points are more prevelent.

Data type "float64" is definitely continuous. Data type "object" is most likely categorical. Data type "int64" is discrete, and so further context is needed to determine whether to treat these columns as continuous or categorical.

In this case, it makes sense to treate "sqft_living", "sqft_lot", "sqft_above", and "sqft_basement" as continuous because there are many different values and these categories are clearly ordinal -- they have an established order from low square footage to high square footage. The same logic applies for "yr_built" and "yr_renovented", I will treat these as continuous for the purpose of this question.

For the categories "view", "waterfront", and "condition", I want to take a closer look at what data these columns contain:

In[14]:

Since "waterfront" is a boolean variable, I will put it in the categorical group.

For "view" and "condition", it looks like both of these variables are a 5-point scale. These variables can be classified as ordinal categorical variables. The higher a house scores on this scale, the more desirable the house would be in theory. However; they already have numeric values assigned to them, so there is no need to put them through an ordinal encoder. Because of this, I'm going to put them into the numeric/continuous group of variables in this case (even though they could technically be classified as categorical ordinal variables). For discrete integer types, it is important to classify them based on context in order to avoid excessive one-hot encoding.

Here is the final list of continuous and categorical variables I will use for this data set:

Split the data into a training and testing set. Use ColumnTransformer to encode categorical variables. Impute missing values using SimpleImputer.

In[28]:
# First, I generate a label vector y containing the target variable 'price'
y = df_sydney.filter(items=['price'])

# Next, I generate a feature matrix X containing all features except for target variable 'price'
X = df_sydney.loc[:,[i for i in df_sydney.columns if i not in ('price')]]

# Split data into training and test set:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,random_state=42)

#Next, I'll use ColumnTransformer and SimpleImputer to create some transformers:
cat_features = [i for i in df_cat.columns]

cont_transformer = Pipeline(
    steps =[("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy='median'))])

cont_transformer_scaled = Pipeline(
    steps =[("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
           ("scaler", StandardScaler())])

cat_transformer = Pipeline(
    steps =[
        ("encoder", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore",sparse_output=False)),
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent'))])

#Two pipelines: one that scales the data and one that doesn't
#This will make it easier to compare how different models perform with scaled / unscaled data
ct = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [
        ("cont", cont_transformer, cont_features),
        ("cat", cat_transformer, cat_features),])

ct_scaled = ColumnTransformer(
        transformers = [
        ("cont", cont_transformer_scaled, cont_features),
        ("cat", cat_transformer, cat_features),])

Evaluate Linear Regression (OLS), Ridge, Lasso and Elasticnet using crossvalidation with the default parameters. Does scaling the data with Standard Scaler help?

To evaluate model performance I will use root mean squared error.

Linear Regression (OLS):

In[29]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error as mse
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

ols = Pipeline(
    steps = [("preprocess", ct), ("model", LinearRegression())])

param_grid = {'model__fit_intercept': [True, False], 'model__positive': [True, False]}

#Cross Validation: 
grid_search = GridSearchCV(ols, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_ols = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_hat = best_ols.predict(X_test)
test_mse = mse(y_test, y_hat)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)

print(f'Testing Set RMSE without scaling: {test_rmse:.2f}')

ols_scaled = Pipeline(
    steps = [("preprocess", ct_scaled), ("model", LinearRegression())])

grid_search_scaled = GridSearchCV(ols_scaled, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
grid_search_scaled.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_ols_scaled = grid_search_scaled.best_estimator_
y_hat_scaled = best_ols_scaled.predict(X_test)
test_mse_scaled = mse(y_test, y_hat_scaled)
test_rmse_scaled = np.sqrt(test_mse_scaled)

print(f'Testing Set RMSE with Standard Scaler: {test_rmse_scaled:.2f}')

test_mse = mse(y_test, y_hat)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)

print(f'Testing Set RMSE without scaling: {test_rmse:.2f}')

elastic_net_scaled = Pipeline(
    steps = [("preprocess", ct_scaled), ("model", ElasticNet())])

grid_search_scaled = GridSearchCV(elastic_net_scaled, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
grid_search_scaled.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_elastic_net_scaled = grid_search_scaled.best_estimator_
y_hat_scaled = best_elastic_net_scaled.predict(X_test)
test_mse_scaled = mse(y_test, y_hat_scaled)
test_rmse_scaled = np.sqrt(test_mse_scaled)

print(f'Testing Set RMSE with Standard Scaler: {test_rmse_scaled:.2f}')

Testing Set RMSE without scaling: 163423.16
Testing Set RMSE with Standard Scaler: 163232.49

Does scaling the data with StandardScaler help?

Yes, in most cases, it does help to scale the data. This is evidenced by the lower RMSE's for the scaled data in most of the models. The one exception was the Ridge model, although the scaled and non-scaled result for Ridge turned out to be nearly identical. The model with the worst performance was Elastic Net, and the model with the best performance was Ridge. However, none of the models are performing exceptionally well. To improve performance further, it might be a good idea to dig a bit deeper into the preprocessing part of the process. For example, I could go back and drop irrelevant variables, and think about encoding my categorical variables differently (perhaps use an ordinal encoder instead of one hot encode).

Preprocess the data (such as treatment of categorical variables / use ColumnTransformer to encode categorical variables)

In[39]:
cont_transformer = Pipeline(
    steps=[("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
           ])

cont_transformer_scaled = Pipeline(
    steps=[("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
           ("scaler", StandardScaler())])

cat_transformer = Pipeline(
    steps=[
        ("onehot", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore")),
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent'))
    ]
)

# The first column transformer does not include scaling, the second transformer does. 
# This will allow me to easily calculate the difference in model performance using scaled and non scaled data.
ct = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [
        ("cont", cont_transformer, cont_vars),
        ("cat", cat_transformer, cat_vars)])

ct_scaled = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [
        ("cont_scaled", cont_transformer_scaled, cont_vars),
        ("cat", cat_transformer, cat_vars)])

How different are the results? How does scaling the continuous features with StandardScaler influence the results?

Between models, the results were different prior to applying StandardScaler; however, after applying StandardScaler each model reached a very similar score (about 76.8% accuracy). All of the models showed performance improvement after applying StandardScaler. These scores were achieved using the default tuning parameters for these models. Performance could be further enhanced by performing cross validation on these tuning parameters.
